title: For Sale:  Griffin Armament QD Blast Shield BNIB
postcontent:
I bought two and only need one. 

http://www.griffinarmament.com/Griffin-Armament-QD-Blast-Shield-p/gaqdbs.htm

The QD Blast Shield was designed to offer significant concussion reduction for the end user and other team members operating in the immediate vicinity. Often team members in CQB environments experience concussion from muzzle blast that is not only deafeningly loud, but also can cause prolonged headaches that can last for days afterwards. 

Especially effective on short barrels, the unique design of the QD Blast Shield directs concussive force forward allowing an end user to rapidly reconfigure muzzle device function. Ultra strong 17-4PH stainless steel provides a robust material to withstand intense use and full auto fire without fear of failure. Fluted geometry in the triangular shield lightens the unit while providing internal front supports for the muzzle device. 

Melonite QPQ surface treatment provides an extremely hard, durable, and attractive finish.

The QD mechanism is fast, positive, and free of wear prone geometry commonly found in ratcheting devices. The QD Blast Shield also comes with a shim set and overtravel stop to refit your A2 compensator for optimal use. 

The Griffin QD Blast Shield is compatible with our line of SDQD mounts in 7.62 and 5.56mm, Including the Flash Comp, Muzzle Brake, Compensating Flash Hider, and Tactical Compensator. It is also compatible with A2 Compensators that fall within the NATO spec blueprinted dimensions. Although many companies manufacture A2 style compensators not all of them are dimensioned properly. Not Compatible with BCM, BCE or PWS muzzle devices. 

Griffin Armament has continued to pursue product development that will enhance hearing safety in tactical and shooting sport situations. The QD Blast Shield is a great product for those that would like to reduce the concussion of their muzzle devices.

postcontent: Excellent condition - 92+%: This is NOT the ‘Sportsman’ or ’11-48’! It was introduced for only a couple of years after the ‘formers’ were discontinued (11-48 in 1968), and only in 12 & 20 ga. This is confirmed by the ‘Barrel Code’ of ‘X -W’ - ‘Dec - 1972’. It was basically the last of the ‘recoil operated’ semi-automatic shotguns. It is very different, with its unique Gold Trigger and ‘MOHAWK 48’ marked on the left side of receiver, and is hard to find. It was followed by the model 58, the first Remington ‘gas operated’ semi-auto shotguns; it was NOT successful. It was quickly replaced by the well-known, and successful, Model 1100 ! It is still VERY ‘Useable / Hunt-able’... the ‘recoil operated’ shotguns ( like the BROWNING A-5) just have a ‘little’ more recoil ! If you have a problem with a 12 Gauge... buy a 20 Gauge! title: For Sale:  1862 C.S Richmond Musket
postcontent:
The C.S. Richmond Musket was manufactured form 1861 to 1865 by the Richmond Armory in Richond, Virginia. This musket was produced in larger numbers than all other Confederate longarms manufactured during the Civil War. The Richmond features a .58 caliber one-piece forged barrel, 39.937" in length rifled w/three grooves, 1 in 66" twist; military style sights; steel triggerguard and barrel bands finished bright; and brass buttplate and nosecap. The percussion lock is marked 1862 to the left of the hammer and "C.S. RICHMOND, VA." to the right of the hammer. The barrel has the "VP" and the eagle head stamping to the left of the breech. The Richmond also features a one piece American walnut oil finished stock. Overall length is 56". 5/16 x 24 nipple and steel ramrod. N/SSA approved. Manufactured by Armi Sport of Italy.

This gun has been used by me only for reenactments in the Battles of New Market, Cedar Creek, Antietam and the 150th Gettysburg.  The only other times are for living history events.  You will enjoy this gun for reenactments or hunting!

title: For Sale/Trade:  Like new Remington 770 in .270
postcontent:
Picked it up as a cheap try-it-out gun August 2012.  Looking to move it along for something else. 

It's had 10 shots through it in two sittings on sunny days, cleaned afterwards, and then just sat.  Has not been hunted with.  Condition is like new.  Synthetic stock, magazine, stock scope Bushnell 3-9x40 (plain reticle) on top.  Standard, detachable magazine is present.  Comes with the other half of the box and the fired brass.   Shoots and grouped well, last four shots were in an inch at a 100 yds with Federal soft points.  Sighted in dead on at 100 yards.

Questions previously asked of me:  

- Not part of the Remington trigger debacle (not that model and made since that issue was identified).  

- No failure to feed, fire, or extract.  

- The bolt has some wobble to it when pulled all the way back.  There is a bolt catch so it will not pull out but this rifle's action is not tight and slick like a more expensive firearm, but you're not paying for the tighter machining tolerances either.  That said, with the cleaning and oiling done to it, it does not grab/catch/bind and will continue to get smoother with cycling, care, and time.

My preference is to transfer at i-5 guns, I-5 exit 111, near Winco/Walmart.  That's an hour south of Seattle for those not familiar with Google Maps.  $20 transfer fee, buyer pays, and photo id with current address required.  I am over in Grays Harbor, up to Federal Way, Maple Valley/Covington, and Enumclaw areas occasionally depending on weekend plans.  I'll travel if it works into my plans (been stood up too many times in the past to do it on my dime and time).  

Fairly firm on price, trying to get my money back out of this purchase to fund something else.  Before contacting me with a low ball offer, I encourage you to look around on Armslist, and search the United States for Remington 770.  This is priced well below the average asking price for the firearm around the state and country and consider I'm already out 25% of my original cash outlay at my listed price.  Not looking for pity but will not take "$150 and meet you in Marysville".
